DCA-1: Incident occurred at 1835 (1335L), first notification was made by Pentagon Police (Thomas Shannon) at 1925 (1425L). The Pentagon Police and Arlington PD received a report of a UAS being operated at 675 N Randolph Street, Arlington, VA. (approximately DCA300003.5). According to reports, the UAS was not being operated above the height of the building (unknown height / floors). It was also initially reported that they had received approval for the operation from the FAA. TSA NCRCC, FAA NCRCC and DCA ATCT were unable to locate any information on the operation. When Arlington PD arrived at the scene (1835Z /1335L),the UAS was flying and they ordered it down and the pilot complied immediately. They estimate that it had been flying for approximately 5 minutes. When FAANCRCC queried them reference having FAA approval, they replied that was not the case as the operator landed the aircraft immediately. POC for the Arlington PD: Lt Dan Murphy,. UAS Operator: Edgar Romero, Washington Digital Media, who stated that he was working for the construction company who was erecting a pedestrian walkway for the owners of the building. MOR completed by DCA. MX notified.

INITIAL/CLKOSEOUT: 1430 Kings Bay Naval Base reported UAS operating inside P-50 and possibly taking video of the sub base. The operator of he UAS was on a boat off the coast. Camden County SO was notified. Camden County SO located the boat and detained the operator. HQ DEN advised JAX to have Camden County SO collect as much info on the operator to be included in the MOR for the FSDO. JAX questioned if the suspect should be detained further, arrested, or released, and HQ DEN advised that was not a decision made at this office. 1717 HQ DEN contacted Special Agent Whigham with NCIS. NCIS confirmed that the UAS did penetrate the confines of P-50 but did not over fly the base and WASP was not activated. NCIS notified that it was fisherman trying to locate fish. Special Agent Whigham. Camden County SO 912-+510-5100. AWO notified.

Owner/operator of Alaska Bush Float Plane Service reported an unauthorized UAS operation in the vicinity of Fish Lake, a private seaplane base. He stated a male parked what looked to be a gray 2010 Ford Expedition, Alaska license plate KGA362, just off the property, and was operating a drone near his float planes. The drone was described as a light green quadcopter approximately 14 inches wide with an elongated center. An employee spoke to the male that was flying the drone and told him he needed to stop. The male landed the drone but then attempted to fly it again. He eventually landed the quadcopter and left. Jason was advised to speak to the Alaska State Troopers about a possible trespassing issue.

The woman stated she had a drone and was going to intercept the FLC while on the ILS. HQ DEN attempted to call the airport manager, negative results. HQ DEN attempted to call local law enforcement (Burlington PD at with negative results. HQ DEN reached out to GSO who was working the aircraft and no reports made by the aircraft or the airfield manager. HQ DEN notified TSOC of the threat against the FAA aircraft. 2224 UPDATE: HQ DEN acquired the callers information (name and number) and notified TSOC. TSA to reach out to their regional coordination center. JH notified.

DCA-1:  US Supreme Court Police reported a UAS at 1344 local.  The UAS was recovered in heavy foliage on the N side of the Supreme Court grounds.  UAS was about the size of a softball red in color.  No operator was identified.  The link describes the UAS.  https://www.amazon.com/Drone-Flying-Operated-Drones-Adults/dp/B07MGQWKM8    DCA ATCT will file a retroactive MOR.
SUMMARY.CEDAR: On Wednesday, July 21, 2021 US Supreme Court reported to US Capitol Police (USCP) Headquarters that a UAS Drone was reported flying in the area of First and Maryland Avenue, NE, Washington, DC and crashed into the northside of the Supreme Court Building.  Officers from US Supreme Court, US Capitol Police, USCP Crime Scene, and USCP JTTF arrived on scene to investigate.  A red drone was found in the bushes and an investigation to locate the operator of the drone was met with negative results.   US Capitol Police did not have any camera footage of the drone.  The investigation was completed and the US Supreme court returned to normal operations at 1430.  The reported UAS's closest range to DCA was 2 nautical miles.  No further action was taken.

REMARKS: DCA-1: ADW Base Police observed a UAS with red and green lights, off the E side of ADW base, DCA121009, while hovering and eventually Sbound. Altitude and type unknown. ADW LEO notified at. 0735Z  ADW Tower reports a UAS with white, red, and green lights, 35-50 feet above AF1 hanger. Base PD investigating. 0803 NCRCC called ADW PD and they confirmed that original sighting over E gate went dark, and reappeared over AF1 hanger about 15-20 minutes later. UAS was detected by electronic means and verified by sightings from two different PD teams. No counter measures used at this time. 0926 Closeout: No more sightings reported. ADW will do MOR. 0929 ADW Tower talked to PAG security and they said that they never saw the UAS that the base security was seeing. PAG security said all they saw were lights from overflight aircraft.
SUMMARY.CEDAR: AT APPROXIMATELY 0637Z ADW'S UAS COUNTERMEASURE SENSORS WERE ALERETED TO AN UNAUTHORIZED UAS OPERATING WITHIN THE BASE PERIMETER. THE ON-SCENE OFFICER INFORMED TOWER, VIA TELEPHONE, OF THE ACTIVITY, BUT WAS UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY INFORMATION AS TO SIZE, TYPE, OR ALTITUDE, EXCEPT THAT THE INTRUDER HAD RED, GREEN, AND WHITE LIGHTS AND WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND. THE UAS WAS ORIGINALLY SPOTED NEAR THE PEARL HARBOR GATE WHICH IS LOCATED NEAR THE SOUTHEAST CORNER OF THE AIRFIELD. VISUAL CONFIRMATION WITH THE UAS LIGHTS WAS REPORTED LOST AT APPROX 0715Z. AN ADDITIONAL SIGHTING WAS MADE AT APPROXIMATLY 0737Z OVER THE AIR FORCE ONE HANGER 19.  THIS SIGHTING WAS CONFRIMED BY ADW SECURITY FORCES. THE VERBAL REPORTS RELAYED TO TOWER MENTIONED RED, GREEN, AND WHITE LIGHT. NO PERCISE DISCRIPTION WAS EVER OBSERVED, EXCEPT THE COLOR OF ITS LIGHTS. THE UAS DISSAPPEARED FROM LAW ENFORCEMENTS VIEW AND NO DIRECT ACTION WAS TAKEN AGAINST THE INTRUDER. ADW ATC CONTROLLERS WERE NEVER ABLE TO VIUSALLY CONFIRM WITH LEO'S REPORTS OF UAS/UAP SIGHTINGS.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary reviewed. At approximately 0637Z ADW UAS countermeasure sensors were alerted to an unauthorized UAS operating within the base perimeter. The on-scene officer informed ATCT, via telephone, of the activity, but was unable to provide any information as to size, type, or altitude, except that the intruder had red, green, and white lights and was traveling southbound. The UAS was originally spotted near the Pearl Harbor gate which is located near the southeast corner of the airfield. Visual confirmation with the UAS lights was reported lost at approximately 0715z. An additional sighting was made at approximately 0737z over the Air Force one hanger 19.  This sighting was confirmed by ADW security forces. The verbal reports relayed to tower mentioned red, green, and white lights. No precise description was ever observed, except the color of its lights. The UAS disappeared from law enforcements view and no direct action was taken against the intruder. ADW ATCT controllers were never able to visually confirm the UAS/UAP sightings. MOR closed.

REMARKS: FAA Flight Check aircraft observed a UAS while conducting inspection of RNAV-A Approach. Aircraft took unknown evasive action. LEO not notified due to the late reporting of event. AWO/JH notified.
SUMMARY.CEDAR: During periodic inspection of the RNAV-A at W31 we had to maneuver to avoid a small remote controlled aircraft. The aircraft was less than 3 feet in wingspan and appeared to be something that could be bought at a hobby shop. There is a house immediately off the departure end of RWY 02 and the aircraft was operating over the house. We were able to avoid the remote aircraft and continued the mission with no further incident. ZDC QC comments, this report was submitted to the Flight Safety Program from a deidentified safety submission 5 days after the event.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary reviewed. N84 was conducting an evaluation of an RNAV-A approach for RWY 2 at W31 airport in ZDC airspace. The RNAV approach for RWY 2 has a Go-around procedure with an initial heading of 360 degrees after initial climb is established. There is a house off the departure end of the runway and N84 encountered a remote control airplane over that house. Evasive maneuvers were taken to avoid the R/C airplane but the flight proceeded normally afterwards. The pilot did not declare a NMAC. The aircraft wasn't receiving ATC services at the time. The report was summitted 5 days after the event. No authorities were notified. MOR closed.
